{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Ally Financial, known as GMAC Financial when it was bailed out for $17 billion, could be harmed if its mortgage unit files for bankruptcy as expected.", "abstract": "Gretchen Morgenson Fair Game column observes Ally Financial, known as GMAC Financial when it was bailed out for $17 billion, could be harmed if its mortgage unit Residential Capital files for bankruptcy as expected; notes for the moment, depositors and creditors of Ally seem relatively unfazed; points out that Ally, which is still 74 percent taxpayer owned following the bailout, will almost certainly have to write a check to escape this mess, and the only question is how big the check will have to be.", "section_name": "Business Day", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Gretchen", "role": "reported", "lastname": "MORGENSON", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By GRETCHEN MORGENSON", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/06/business/troubled-mortgage-unit-threatens-ally-financial.html", "lead_paragraph": "Ally Financial, known as GMAC Financial when it was bailed out for $17 billion, could be harmed if its mortgage unit files for bankruptcy as expected.", "headline": {"seo": "Troubled Mortgage Unit Threatens Ally Financial", "main": "Mortgage Unit Troubles Ally Financial", "print_headline": "Mortgage Unit Troubles Ally Financial", "content_kicker": "Fair Game", "kicker": "Fair Game"}, "_id": "53f66e4438f0d821a37b21af", "word_count": "1082", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2010/04/19/business/morgenson/morgenson-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2010/04/19/business/morgenson/morgenson-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 900, "url": "images/2010/04/19/business/morgenson/morgenson-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2010/04/19/business/morgenson/morgenson-articleLarge.